document.description: I have a cure for insomnia. It’s probably worth millions of dollars but I’m giving it to you free. It isn’t warm milk or chamomile tea. It’s list making. List stuff from your life like all your teachers or all the live music you’ve seen or all the Paul Newman movies you’ve watched. Okay, it may not put you to sleep, but at least you’ll entertain yourself while you’re awake instead of worrying your way through the night. Please use the open space below to share your first 50 words on the topic “insomnia.”

**1- Create a Developer Account**

**2-**  **Create an Apex Class**

- In Salesforce, navigate to Setup.

- In the Quick Find box, search for " **Apex Classes**" and select it.

- Click on " **New**" to create a new Apex class.

![](RackMultipart20230523-1-yruz1b_html_8c98b472259d3c40.png)

- Write the Apex class code that handles the logic for our webhook

(Paste this code and click save)

```
for(int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
     std::cout << i << std::endl;
}
```

![](RackMultipart20230523-1-yruz1b_html_8ef9072145d59e4f.png)

**3- Create a site**

- In Salesforce Setup, search for " **Sites**" and select it

- Click on " **New**"

![](RackMultipart20230523-1-yruz1b_html_ae80f9ac0529f3ed.png)

- Configure the site settings, including the Site Labe, Site Name and all required fields.

Save the site configuration.

**3- Assign Webhook class to Site**

- Click on the name of the site you created in Step 2.

![](RackMultipart20230523-1-yruz1b_html_ffc738de90d6b461.png)

- Under the " **Public Access Settings**" section, click on " **Apex Class Access.**"

![](RackMultipart20230523-1-yruz1b_html_c1693dc06a64d5dd.png)

![](RackMultipart20230523-1-yruz1b_html_63e6ce22c56d0f5b.png)

**-** Click on **"Edit"** andAdd the Apex class you created in Step 1 to the "Enabled Apex Classes" list.

![](RackMultipart20230523-1-yruz1b_html_21373e3b94faac1a.png)

![](RackMultipart20230523-1-yruz1b_html_8f20a7d0f0a90f2a.png)

- Save the Apex class access settings.

**4-**  **Create a Page Layout for "Event" in Account Object Manager**

- In Salesforce Setup, search for " **Object Manager**" and select it.
- Locate and select the " **Account**" object.
- Go to the " **Page Layouts**" section and click on " **New**" to create a new page layout for events.
- Save the page layout.

**5-**  **Create Custom Fields for the New Page Layout**

- In Salesforce Setup, search for " **Object Manager**" and select it.
- Locate and select the " **Account**" object.
- Go to the " **Fields & Relationships**" section.
- Click on " **New**" to create a new custom field.
- Create the following custom fields for the " **Event**" page layout you created in Step 4:

1. Field 1: event\_name ( dataType : Text)
2. Field 2: request (dataType : Long Text Area)
3. Field 3: response (dataType : Long Text Area)

- Save the custom fields.

**Note !!**

When you create field in next page 4 select the page layout you create it **,**" **See screenshot below**"

 ![Shape 2](RackMultipart20230523-1-yruz1b_html_1da621f9e963a852.gif)

![](RackMultipart20230523-1-yruz1b_html_5d4f524245b829a5.png)

**Your listener URL will be your Salesforce**  **Site\_address/services/apexrest/urlMapping.**

urlMApping in this EXample= **webhook**
